The value of ‘this’ is not set when a function is written. It is set when the function is called. Four rules decide what it becomes – and they have a strict order of priority.

4 min read
1 hour ago

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Photo by Felicia Buitenwerf on UnsplashYou have a method that uses this to refer to its object. Call it through the object and this is correct. Store it in a variable, call it from there, and this is suddenly the global object or undefined. Same function, character for character. The only thing that changed was how you called it. That is the entire key to understanding this – and most explanations skip right past it.

🎙 This article is the companion to the Oh, That’s Why. podcast episode ‘The this Keyword – Part 1' – hosted by Alex Vega. The podcast builds the whole model through the meaning of the word “here” before any code. Link in the footer.
Last week we covered prototypes and the prototype chain – how JavaScript finds properties and methods on objects. This week we look at what this refers to inside those methods, and why the same method can see a completely different this depending on how it is invoked.

Think about the word “here.” The sentence “I am here” has no fixed meaning on its own – “here” depends entirely on where you are standing when you say it. Say it in a kitchen, it means the kitchen.
Say the identical sentence in a garden, it means the garden. Write it on a card and carry it around, and every reader fills in “here” based on their own location.
As Alex explains in the episode, this works exactly the same way. A function is the card. The word this inside it does not get its meaning when the function is written – it gets filled in every time the function is called, based on how that specific call is made.
this is determined by the call, not the definition
This is the one idea everything else depends on. The value of this depends on how a function is invoked at runtime, not where it was defined. To find this, you find the call site and apply four rules in priority order.
The four binding rules
Default binding – the fallback. A plain standalone function call, with nothing before it, gets the global object as this in non-strict mode, or undefined in strict mode (the default inside modules and classes).
function show() {
console.log(this);
}show(); // global object (non-strict) or undefined (strict mode)
Implicit binding – the everyday case. When a function is called as a method, this is the object to the left of the dot at the moment of the call.
const user = {
name: “Alex”,
greet() {
return `Hi, I’m ${this.name}`;
},
};user.greet(); // “Hi, I’m Alex” – this is user (object before the dot)
Explicit binding – call, apply, and bind let you state what this should be directly, overriding implicit binding. (Full coverage next week.)
function greet() {
return `Hi, I’m ${this.name}`;
}const user = { name: “Alex” };
greet.call(user); // “Hi, I’m Alex” – this explicitly set to user
New binding – calling a function with new creates a fresh object and sets this to it for the duration of the call.
function User(name) {
this.name = name; // this is the brand-new object
} const alex = new User(“Alex”);
console.log(alex.name); // “Alex”
The priority order
When more than one rule could apply, this is the order, highest to lowest:
1. new binding – this is the newly created object
2. explicit binding – call / apply / bind set this
3. implicit binding – the object before the dot
4. default binding – global object, or undefined in strict modeTo resolve any this, walk down the list: called with new? Explicitly bound? Called as a method? None of those? Default. One detail on new: if the constructor explicitly returns an object, that object replaces the new one. If it returns a primitive, the return is ignored and you still get the new object.
The single most common this bug is losing this when a method is passed as a callback. You pass object.method as a reference to setTimeout, an event listener, or forEach. When that code later calls it, it calls a bare function – not object.method – so default binding applies and this is no longer your object.
The link between a method and its object lives in the call (object.method()), not in the function. Pass the bare function and the link is gone.
The value of this is not decided when the function is written – it is decided when the function is called. Find the call, and you find the this.
Have you been bitten by the callback version of this bug – a method that worked until you passed it to setTimeout or an event listener? Does the ‘find the call site’ rule make it clearer why it happened?

Next week – Part 2. call, apply, and bind in full: the three tools that take direct control of this. Plus arrow functions, which do not have their own this at all and inherit it from the surrounding scope – the change that quietly fixes the callback bug.
🎙 The podcast walks through all four rules and the priority order through the ‘here’ analogy, and traces the callback bug step by step. If the four rules are still blurring together, the audio makes the priority order stick. Find Oh, That’s Why. wherever you listen to podcasts.

Thanks for reading. Stop asking what this means in the function – start asking how the function was called. That single shift is the whole thing.
